subsection.p:
The volume constraint is
\boxed{\pi r^2h=V.}
The surface area is
\boxed{A(r,h)=2\pi r^2+2\pi rh.}
The first term is the top and bottom. The second term is the side.

What to hand in. Your report should include:
\begin{array}{ll} 1. \amp \text{a labeled diagram,}\\ 2. \amp \text{the objective function,}\\ 3. \amp \text{the constraint,}\\ 4. \amp \text{the derivative or Lagrange multiplier equations,}\\ 5. \amp \text{the final dimensions,}\\ 6. \amp \text{a check that the point is a minimum,}\\ 7. \amp \text{a short interpretation.} \end{array}
The interpretation is not optional. In a modeling problem, the formula and the story must agree.

A seed example: fitting a calibration plane. A sensor output z depends on two inputs x and y. A lab records the data
\begin{array}{c|c|c} x \amp y \amp z \\ \hline 0 \amp 0 \amp 2\\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 3\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4\\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 6\\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 7 \end{array}
Fit a plane \boxed{z=ax+by+c.} For the i-th data point, the residual is ax_i+by_i+c-z_i. The squared-error function is \boxed{E(a,b,c)=\sum_{i=1}^5(ax_i+by_i+c-z_i)^2.}

For this data set, expanding gives
E(a,b,c) \amp = 6a^2+6ab+8ac-46a \amp\qquad +3b^2+6bc-34b \amp\qquad +5c^2-44c+114.
At a critical point, E_a=E_b=E_c=0. Compute: E_a=12a+6b+8c-46, E_b=6a+6b+6c-34, E_c=8a+6b+10c-44. So the normal equations are
\boxed{ \begin{aligned} 12a+6b+8c\amp=46,\\ 6a+6b+6c\amp=34,\\ 8a+6b+10c\amp=44. \end{aligned} }
Solving gives \boxed{a=\frac75,\qquad b=\frac{37}{15},\qquad c=\frac95.} So the best-fit plane is \boxed{z=\frac75x+\frac{37}{15}y+\frac95.}

